In this review, we first briefly summarize key aspects of motor-driven molecular focusing and steric confinement that operate on proteins that are dozens or even hundreds of nanometers apart (Figure 1, right). We then describe, in detail, the origin of membrane-mediated clustering forces and identify the preconditions for their appearance in specific perturbations of the membrane’s state (Figure 1, middle). Recent experiments have indeed shown that physical membrane properties that are expected to affect membrane-mediated clustering, such as viscosity and bending fluctuations, strongly influence cell functions. A picture is starting to emerge of how the cell manipulates membrane-mediated interactions to regulate its physiology. It is also clear that relevant experiments typically involve a combination of simultaneously contributing forces. Computer simulations are therefore an important aid in predicting the strength of the forces under model conditions, and for interpreting the consequences of experimentally changing membrane properties. We hope that placing membrane-mediated forces in context among better-known mechanisms of protein clustering will promote recognition within the life sciences’ community of nature’s inventive exploitation of these forces in support of cellular life.
Molecular Motors and Steric Confinement
Some examples of how the cell uses membranes to distribute and locally concentrate material are well known. For motor-driven molecular focusing, membrane components interact directly or indirectly with the cortical actin cytoskeleton. An early example of this is the phenomenon of patching and capping [5]. A specific actin organization may then drive them to cluster in areas of the plasma membrane. This has been particularly well studied in the case of glycosyl-phosphatidylinositol (GPI)-anchored proteins [6]. An aster-type of actin organization has been hypothesized, and experimental testing was provided for such a model in which GPI-anchored proteins would be molecularly focused to the centers of the asters [3]. Interestingly, a later study then provided evidence for a transbilayer coupling-dependent link of exoplasmic leaflet-associated GPI-anchored proteins to the cortical actin cytoskeleton; for transmembrane proteins, a direct link to actin also led to molecular focusing [7]. Apart from this well-studied aster hypothesis, other actin configurations could also lead to clustering, such as dynamic linear confinement along actin cables [8].
