Membrane-Mediated Clustering Forces
The third category of indirect clustering mechanism (i.e., membrane-mediated interactions) occurs in the absence of any extramembranous drivers such as motors or steric blockers, and arises solely from the thermodynamic properties of a membrane. Proteins embedded in or associated with a membrane generally perturb its state and change the free energy of the combined system (membrane and proteins). If the free energy is lowered significantly (compared with kB T[198_TD$IF], where kB is Boltzmann’s constant and T is absolute temperature) when the proteins are brought into spatial proximity, it signifies a membrane-mediated attractive force and possible clustering mechanism (Figure 2A). Each type of force has its origin in a particular perturbation of the membrane’s state. We refer to them as capillary forces, depletion forces, curvature forces, and thermal Casimir-like forces. Although these forces are usually considered separately, it is important to keep in mind that they may act in combination, as a membrane
