Capillary Forces A membrane domain has a very well-defined interfacial boundary with an interfacial line tension: the free energy caused by a strong variation in composition across the interface (Figure 2B). The interfacial tension [19_TD$IF]tends to reduce the domain perimeter length and can thus generate a force. In colloidal chemistry, such an appearance is known as a capillary force, and gives rise to a wealth of capillary phenomena, including capillary condensation and wetting. Different types of membrane domains can lead to the generation of capillary forces, including the raft domain, the lipid shell, and interfacially active proteins.
The lipid raft hypothesis has had an immense impact on the field of membrane biology [10]. In its initial formulation, it was suggested that mixtures of certain types of amphiphilic molecules would phase[20_TD$IF]-separate into nanodomains, preferentially enriched in sphingolipids and cholesterol (the raft lipids) that coexist in thermodynamic equilibrium, with the bulk membrane enriched in phospholipids. Such phase separation is driven by the difference of the molecular packing of the raft lipids and the bulk membrane lipids. More recently, the view has been advocated that proteins (or other inducers) directly influence raft lipid distributions [11], and that protein-induced proximity between raft lipids enables ‘raft connectivity’, which then contributes to the stabilization of larger protein–lipid raft assemblies that carry out biological functions [12–14].
Where would line tension come from in the case of raft domains? An intuitively obvious situation is the one where the raft domain has a larger hydrophobic thickness compared with the surrounding bulk lipids. Here, a height mismatch exists at the domain boundary that is energetically unfavorable because of hydrophobic segments of the acyl chains being exposed to the aqueous environment, generating the interfacial boundary force (or line tension).
How would raft domain formation lead to clustering? If several small raft domains exist in a membrane, bringing them together into one bigger domain reduces the total domain perimeter length, and is therefore energetically more favorable (Figure 2B).
Multicomponent lipid membranes have the capacity to form domains associated with equilibrium phase coexistence, notably the liquid-ordered (lo) – liquid-disordered (ld) coexistence known from domains in multicomponent vesicles in vitro [15]. The lo phase has often been identified with the above-mentioned raft phase. Even at conditions off phase coexistence, such nanodomains can be stabilized by the presence of membrane proteins [16], which therefore embed themselves in the bulk of the domain, and possess a boundary region with characteristics different from the bulk lipid phase. The term ‘lipid shell’ has been coined to describe this situation [17]. At close distances, bridging between such nanodomains gives rise to strong attraction between proteins with a free energy gain of lD, where l is the line tension and D is the lateral extent of the protein. This mechanism can thus give rise to aggregation of specific proteins into clusters in a lipid-sorted environment, as in the lipid rafts described above. However, it should be emphasized that this clustering mechanism is different from partitioning of proteins into the lipid domains, which is usually envisioned in the raft hypothesis.
