Analysis of different biological membrane preparations have demonstrated that many cell membranes have lipid compositions that are close to lo –ld coexistence in equilibrium driven by lipid chain melting and cholesterol [20–23]. Similarly, the abundance of lipid components suggests that a multitude of lipid phase separation phenomena can take place. In living cells, macroscopic phase separation may be impeded by enzyme activity, interaction with cytoskeleton components, and/or exocytotic and endocytotic membrane trafficking, etc. [21,24]. However, at nanometric length scales of proteins, the propensity for phase separation can be exploited, and proteins can act as nucleation seeds for disk-like lipid nanodomains and thus generate capillary forces. The energy cost of this lipid domain boundary per unit length is typically in order of a few [20_TD$IF]pico-Newton (pN), which is comparable with thermal energy per nanometer. Examples for inducers of disk-like lipid nanodomain formation are the bacterial Shiga and cholera toxins. By oligovalent binding to the glycosphingolipids Gb3 or GM1, respectively, which are their cellular receptors, these toxins induce macroscopic phase separation [25], but most likely also nanoscopic domain formation [26]. Another example is the interfacially active Na+[197_TD$IF]/K+-ATPase, which is sorted into clusters in simple raft mixtures [27].
Lipid Depletion Forces Membrane lipids that are spatially confined and conformationally constrained between nearby integral membrane proteins may escape via diffusion, thereby driving the proteins to cluster so as to maximize their own configurational and translational entropy (Figure 2C). Lipid molecules close to the ‘hard’ interface of integral membrane proteins are conformationally restricted. When these lipids are mobile relative to the proteins, they may diffuse away so as to increase their entropy. The effective expulsion of lipids from between nearby proteins leads to an effective short-range attraction between the proteins. These short-range, membrane-mediated depletion forces between proteins were first recognized by Marcelja [28], and have been confirmed by theoretical and computer simulation studies [29–31]. Although it has been difficult to verify this interaction force experimentally, it is expected to play a crucial role in aggregation of membrane proteins. This mechanism is impeded if the integral proteins have associated annular lipids at their boundary region that are translationally immobile with respect to the protein. In other words: lipid depletion-induced forces are negated if the entropy penalty of lipid immobilization is compensated by the enthalpy of protein–lipid interaction. When the hydrophobic thickness of an integral membrane protein differs from that of the fluid lipid bilayer, the boundary lipids will be deformed with a free energy cost (Figure 2C). This can facilitate the shortrange depletion force.
Depletion forces generate an effective attraction between integral membrane proteins that arises if both proteins and their adjacent lipids are freely mobile, but in some way conformationally incompatible, such as possessing different hydrophobic thicknesses. Proteins that are not free to diffuse in the membrane, such as those bound to the membrane-associated cytoskeleton (e.g., ankyrin; [32]) or to the extracellular matrix (e.g., integrins [33]), do not experience depletion forces, nor do proteins that assemble an attached annular layer of lipids [34,35]. The strength of the depletion interactions depends on the protein-induced conformational constriction of lipid chains due to hydrophobic mismatch (Figure 2C) and steric effects (several kB T), and on the size of the proteins of interest.
