Curvature Forces Many proteins induce local curvature in a membrane. This curvature can arise both when peripheral proteins bind to, or integral membrane proteins are embedded in, the membrane. In response to the unfavorable deformation, and to minimize the membrane’s total elastic energy, the membrane generates an effective interaction between these proteins (Figure 2D). This force depends only on the protein’s curvature imprint and is not dependent on whether it is a peripheral or integral membrane protein. Biomembranes are thin, fluid bilayer interfaces that are adapted to a specific morphology. A symmetric, homogeneous membrane has its minimum energy when it is flat, and any shape deformation incurs an elastic energy penalty that is often described by the Canham-Helfrich Hamiltonian [36,37]. For membranes without holes or edges, such as closed vesicles or cells, this takes the form
