Membrane proteins can locally deform the membrane by different mechanisms [40], such as strong specific binding [26], or asymmetric partitioning into the hydrophobic core [41]. In response, the membrane changes the distribution of these proteins to minimize its overall elastic energy. This mechanism drives the proteins to associate or dissociate, depending on the lateral protein shape and the magnitude of the induced curvature.
The first theoretical prediction of the force between weakly curvature-inducing membrane proteins (small contact angles a in Figure 2D) showed it to be monotonically repulsive at all distances for isotropic curvature [42,43], and attractive for proteins with an elongated shape and an anisotropic curvature imprint [43,44]. Curvature-mediated forces can therefore play a major role in driving anisotropic membrane proteins to cluster, e.g., BAR domain proteins and dynamin [45].
For proteins that induce high curvature (large contact angles a in Figure 2D), computer simulations have shown that isotropic (e.g., spherical) nano-objects experience an attractive force that drives them to self-assemble on a lipid bilayer [46]. This force is attractive only for contact angles greater or equal to 90 degrees, and repulsive otherwise [47]. This is an ideal situation for adsorbed colloidal and micron-sized gold particles. In such cases, it has indeed been shown experimentally and in simulations that their self-assembly is driven by curvaturemediated interactions [48]. By contrast, contact angles above 90 degrees are highly unlikely to be achieved by membrane proteins with sizes below 10 nm.
Overall, current theories of curvature-induced protein clustering explain many observed effects, but need to be extended in certain cases, such as including more details of the interactions of a single protein with the membrane [39]. Recent work also shows that the attraction is quantitatively modified when many proteins interact simultaneously [49,50], but an accurate understanding of the behavior in this regime is still missing [51].
Parallel-aligned proteins that are elongated in the plane of the membrane experience attractive curvature-mediated forces [44,52]. Such ‘membrane nematogens’ have roles in intracellular
