Curvature-mediated forces between proteins with shallow isotropic curvature imprints are in general repulsive. However, it is energetically favorable for these proteins to partition into precurved membranes, provided that these have been induced by other membrane bending modalities [56]. Recent experiments have also pointed to the involvement of membrane curvature in the clustering of E-cadherin molecules that bridge two apposed cells [57]. Transmembrane E-cadherin bonds are driven to form domains by the modification of the membrane shape, leading to the proposal of a regulatory role for membrane bending fluctuations in controlling cell adhesion [58].
Thermal Casimir-like Forces Biological membranes undergo ceaseless, long-range cooperative thermal fluctuations [59]. Proteins that modify these fluctuations experience effective forces that may drive them to cluster in order to maximize the entropy of the membrane’s fluctuations (Figure 2E). These forces act over distances several times the size of the proteins, and can be sufficiently strong to draw them into close proximity and keep them clustered against the random thermal diffusion of the membrane’s constituents [60]. In the case of the plasma membrane, although the attached cortical cytoskeleton suppresses its long wavelength fluctuations on length scales of 100 nm, on the scale relevant to membrane-associated proteins this suppression is negligible. Membrane conformational fluctuations have typically been dismissed as noise. Experimental investigation of fluctuation forces has been slow because the contributing effects are hard to disentangle, and relevant theoretical predictions are often obscured by their mathematical complexity [60,61]. Additionally, while clustering mechanisms such as motor-driven molecular focusing, steric hindrance, and raft domains can now be directly visualized, this is not yet possible for membrane fluctuations, at least for those that operate at the nanoscale. In this section, we discuss experiments that have tested theoretical predictions that the spatiallylocalized suppression of membrane fluctuations can generate strong attractive forces between membrane-associated nano-objects, such as proteins. We attempt to render the thermodynamic origin of these fluctuation forces more intuitive.
Fluctuation-induced forces were first recognized by Casimir, who described the attraction experienced by two parallel, uncharged conductors in a vacuum that confines quantum fluctuations of the electromagnetic field [62]. Subsequently, Casimir-like forces were postulated to arise universally in structured fluids characterized by long-range thermal fluctuations [63–65]. We designate these forces as thermal Casimir-like forces.
These phenomena were originally proposed in the context of critical mixtures [66] that can produce attractions between membrane proteins at critical compositions [67]. However, critical conditions for a lipid membrane require a tight control over lipid composition, and it is not known to date how likely such conditions are in complex biological membranes. It is therefore important to point out that cellular membranes are highly structured fluid interfaces that exhibit several types of configurational fluctuation at physiological temperatures, each of which can give rise to thermal Casimir-like forces without the need to invoke critical conditions. At distances that are large compared with the membrane thickness, membrane fluctuations
