are well described as undulation modes, which are observable by light microscopy. Proteins that modify this undulation spectrum experience an attractive force [42]. This force is weak when the proteins are far apart, and it cannot overcome the proteins’ translational entropy. However, at small separations, the force becomes much stronger [60,64], and may be a driving force for protein clustering.
An important missing factor in current descriptions of thermal Casimir-like forces at close distances, is that the membrane’s internal degrees of freedom play an important role, and that membrane fluctuation spectra therefore can no longer be described only by undulations [68]. At mesoscopic length scales (Figure 1, middle), several other degrees of freedom contribute to the membrane fluctuation spectrum (e.g., peristaltic thickness fluctuations, local protrusion modes, lipid density fluctuations, and fluctuations of lipid tilt) [68–71]. Proteins that suppress several of these fluctuations would feel a correspondingly stronger force. For example, peripheral membrane proteins, via interdigitation of sequences into the apposing monolayer, or integral membrane proteins can suppress peristaltic thickness fluctuations in addition to undulations.
It may be asked why different types of membrane protein that experience thermal Casimir-like forces do not all cluster nonspecifically into one membrane patch? Several arguments can be considered in this context. First, proteins must be brought within a distance of a few times their own diameter to experience thermal Casimir-like force-driven interactions. This could be achieved by actin-driven molecular focusing [72]. Second, proteins must be rigid and adsorb tightly to the membrane surface at least a few nanometers in linear extent [60]. Small proteins whose extra- or intracellular domains are displaced from the membrane’s surface by at least 1 nm are expected to experience weak or even negligible thermal Casimir-like clustering forces. Third, conventional short-range subnanometric clustering forces (Figure 1, left) that exploit the chemical structure of interacting partners would come into play once nano-objects (such as membrane proteins) have been driven to close distances by thermal Casimir-like forces. Only in some cases will these subnanometric clustering forces then stabilize interactions. In other terms, thermal Casimir-like forces are expected to increase the efficiency by which the chemical interaction space is explored.
Identifying the contribution of thermal Casimir-like forces to protein clustering on membranes is difficult because theoretical models are not easy to relate to experimental setups [73,74]. It is currently still impossible to locally image peristaltic thickness fluctuations, local protrusion modes, lipid density fluctuations, and fluctuations of lipid tilt directly. Computer simulations have proven to be useful in filling this gap. For example, all-atom molecular dynamics simulations can be exploited to get indications of the ability of a protein to suppress aspects of the membrane fluctuation spectrum. One can then use synthetic chemistry to create chemical entities with tuned abilities to suppress membrane fluctuations, and measure clustering under corresponding experimental conditions. An example for this is given below. Computer simulations can also be used to provide quantitative estimates for experimental observations on thermal Casimir-like forces in situations where theoretical modeling is limited [60]. Overall, computer simulations allow the various contributing factors to membrane-mediated forces to be teased apart in a controlled way. Thereby, they help to identify experimental properties that are most useful in testing the hypothesis that a given biological phenomenon involves contributions from thermal Casimir-like forces.
The preconditions for thermal Casimir-like forces to arise between membrane-attached nanoobjects (such as proteins) are remarkably few compared with the other membrane-mediated
