forces. They require only that the membrane be in a fluid state, and that the associated proteins or nanoparticles are rigid and tightly bound to the membrane surface in order to suppress the apposed membrane’s thermal fluctuations. Since most cellular membranes are fluid, it is highly likely that thermal Casimir-like forces play an as yet unrecognized role in many cellular processes. Because these forces arise from the suppression of thermal fluctuations, their bare strength is typically of the order of a few kBT, which is weak. However, they increase strongly at separation distances of the interacting particles in the mesoscopic nanometer range (Figure 1, middle), and at separation distances in the range of the size of the interacting proteins (typically 5–10 nm), they become as strong as van der Waals, screened electrostatic, or hydrogen bonding forces [60]. Importantly, thermal Casimir-like forces increase inversely with the separation of the apposed straight-edge boundaries of nano-objects (such as proteins), and not with their center-to-center distance.
In a recent study, evidence was provided for a role of thermal Casimir-like forces in the clustering of tightly membrane-associated Shiga toxin molecules [60]. The capacity of this bacterial protein toxin (which binds to the glycosphingolipid Gb3 as a cellular receptor) to suppress membrane fluctuations was predicted from computer simulations. Experimentally, it was then shown that the membrane-mediated clustering of Shiga toxin molecules was lost when Gb3 receptor species were used in which the toxin-binding sugar part was separated by a flexible linker from the membrane-inserted ceramide part, even at surface densities of Shiga toxin molecules that were similar to ones obtained on natural Gb3. These findings thus demonstrate that the tight mechanical coupling of toxin molecules onto membranes is crucial for clustering, likely by suppressing fluctuation modes. Several other pathogenic [75,76] and cellular [77] lectins exist that interact with glycosphingolipids for their uptake into cells, and it is likely that this clustering mechanism also applies in these cases.
Concluding Remarks
Unlike direct protein–protein interactions, membrane-mediated forces are not explicitly dependent on the protein’s biochemical nature. They arise instead when proteins physically perturb the membrane’s thermodynamic state. Proteins with quite different biochemical functions can thereby cluster via the mechanisms of capillary, depletion, curvature, or thermal Casimir-like forces. Of these types, the thermal Casimir-like forces are the least well explored. Recent experimental evidence has strongly suggested that thermal Casimir-like forces contribute to the formation of endocytic sites by which Shiga toxin enters cells [60].
Thermal Casimir-like forces are likely regulated by acute modulation of protein or membrane properties. Indeed, local membrane composition and structure are expected to play a crucial role in determining the magnitude of these forces. Protein properties such as conformation and structural rigidity may be modulated by phosphorylation or ligand binding, while membrane properties may be modulated by changes in local lipid composition via the action of flippases, phospholipases, or vesicular trafficking. ATP-consuming processes in the cell coupled to the cellular cytoskeleton may also modify the membrane’s physical state [78].
Since the advent of the Singer-Nicholson fluid mosaic model, it has been known that the cell relies on the fluid state of lipid membranes for the lateral displacement of membrane-associated proteins, and this despite the fact that membranes are a densely packed protein–lipid composite material [79]. It now also seems clear that shape and rigidity of membrane proteins are tuned to perturb membrane fluctuations in order to generate attractive thermal Casimir-like forces. As opposed to direct protein–protein interactions, these forces have a generic nature, and can therefore be exploited by proteins of different sequence or function.
Outstanding Questions
How can membrane-mediated forces be experimentally distinguished from each other on cellular membranes, and measured over distances of the protein size?
What is the full range of mechanisms by which biologically-relevant raft domains are built, and what is the role of membrane-mediated forces?
How exactly does a regimen of interactions between multiple nano-objects affect curvature-mediated forces?
What is the full range of biological processes to which thermal Casimir-like fluctuation forces contribute?
