A number of outstanding questions can be identified (see Outstanding Questions). How can membrane-mediated forces be experimentally distinguished from each other on cellular membranes, and measured over distances of the protein size? What is the full range of mechanisms by which biologically-relevant raft domains are built? How exactly does a regimen of interactions between multiple nano-objects affect curvature-mediated forces? What is the full range of biological processes to which thermal Casimir-like fluctuation forces contribute? High-end experimentation will be required to address these questions. Such techniques include force sensors to measure attraction in the pico-Newton range between nanometerspaced nano-objects, and super-resolution live cell imaging to measure how nano-objects may influence each other’s trajectories on membranes once they are at nanometric distances. Theoretical modeling and computer simulations will also play a role in revealing the presence of potentially unexpected interactions that arise on mesoscopic length scales.
